fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Therefore, it remains to show that P is a proposition. Without loss of generality, we may assume that we have some h: P. By Corollary , we may fix x:A and prove that 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen f x\right \rparen \mathclose {}
,\epsilon 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen fx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\cong _{\mathsf {fiber}\,f\,
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen fx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x,\mathsf {refl}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 is a proposition. Of course, this is a retract of the identification type 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen f x\right \rparen \mathclose {}
,\epsilon 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen fx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
=_{\mathsf {fiber}\,f\,
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen fx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x,\mathsf {refl}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 and so by Lemma  it is enough to prove that the latter is a proposition. In fact, we will deduce this via Lemma  by observing that the fiber of f at fx is contractible: using our assumption h:P and the distributivity of products over sums, we may construct a retraction of f exhibiting f as biinvertible and thus by Corollary  contractible.

We must check that for every b:B, the fiber of f at b is a proposition. Fixing u_0,u_1:\mathsf {fiber}\,f\,b we must check that u_0=u_1. We let 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen a_0,p_0\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\equiv  u_0 and 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen a_1,p_1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\equiv  u_1 so that we have p_0\colon  fa_0=b and p_1\colon  fa_1=b. Invoking the path object structure on fibers (Example ), it suffices to exhibit the following data:

As f is an embedding, the map \mathsf {act}_{f}\colon  a_0 = a_1 \to  fa_0 = fa_1 has an inverse 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \mathsf {act}_{f}^{-1},\epsilon ,\eta ,\chi \right \rparen \mathclose {}
.

We first define the sections s_{x,y}\colon  fx = fy \to  x = y. Because f is assumed to be propositional, we have by Example  an assignment \phi _{x,y}: \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen h:fx=fy\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen h:fx=fy\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen h:fx=fy\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen h:fx=fy\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}} 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x,\mathsf {refl}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\cong _{\mathsf {fiber}\,f\,
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen fx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y,h^{-1}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
. We therefore define s_{x,y}h :\equiv  
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \phi _{x,y}h\right \rparen \mathclose {}
.1; the witness of sectionhood can be constructed using 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \phi _{x,y}h\right \rparen \mathclose {}
.2 modulo some identification algebra.

To construct the retractions r_{x,y}\colon  fx=fy\to  x = y, we note by our assumption that we have an assignment \psi _{x,y}:\mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen h:fx=fy\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen h:fx=fy\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen h:fx=fy\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen h:fx=fy\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}} 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x,\mathsf {refl}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 =_{\mathsf {fiber}\,f\,
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen fx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
} 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y,h^{-1}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
, and we define r_{x,y}h :\equiv  \mathsf {act}_{-.1}
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \psi _{x,y}h\right \rparen \mathclose {}
. It remains to show that for all x,y:A and h\colon  x =y, we have \mathsf {act}_{-.1}
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \psi _{x,y}h\right \rparen \mathclose {}
=h. By induction on h it suffices to show that for all x:A we have \mathsf {act}_{-.1}
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \psi _{x,x}\mathsf {refl}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 = \mathsf {refl}. We will deduce that \psi _{x,x}\mathsf {refl} = \mathsf {refl} from our assumption that f\colon  A\to  B is propositional and thus fibred in sets via Lemma .

Let \epsilon  \colon  f\circ  f^{-1} = 1_{B} be the counit of the inverse to f\colon  A\to  B. Given b:B, we must show that the fiber of f over b is contractible; the centre of contraction is given by the pair 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen f^{-1} x, \epsilon  x\right \rparen \mathclose {}
, and the required paths can be constructed via the univalence principle for fibers using the unit \eta \colon  f^{-1}\circ  f = 1_{A}, the coherence \chi \colon  \mathsf {act}_{f}\circ \eta \sim \epsilon \circ  f, and the naturality of homotopies.

We must check that the product \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:B\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}\mathsf {isTruncated}\,n\,
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \mathsf {fiber}\,f\,x\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 is a proposition; indeed, this is a product of propositions (Corollary ) as being an n-truncated type is a proposition (Lemma ).

For any precategory C, the type \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen D : \mathsf {Precategory}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen D : \mathsf {Precategory}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen D : \mathsf {Precategory}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen D : \mathsf {Precategory}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{D\cong  C} of isomorphisms of precategories onto C is contractible.

